# Preview rules (fleet-reports-hub)

## Rule 1 — Ask before any preview

Before showing any preview, diagram, or visual mockup, ask the user exactly:

**"Would you like me to show a visual preview of this first?"**

- Only show a preview if the user says yes.
- Never show ASCII box diagrams, text trees, or code-only previews as a substitute for a real visual.

## Rule 2 — Previews are real HTML files, not ASCII

When the user **requests** a preview:

- Generate a **real `.html` file`** that opens in a browser — not ASCII art, box diagrams, text trees, or pseudocode layouts.
- Location: `previews/`
- Name format: `preview-{feature-name}-{YYYY-MM-DD}.html` (use kebab-case for feature-name).
- The file must:
  - Use real UI elements: inputs, buttons, tables, cards, labels — sized and styled proportionally.
  - Link the app stylesheet for tokens: `<link rel="stylesheet" href="../src/index.css">` (adjust relative path from `previews/` as needed so variables match the app).
  - Keep inputs only slightly taller than their text (e.g. height ≈ `font-size + 8px` max for compact fields; labels ~9–10px uppercase muted per project norms).
  - **Use only existing CSS variables / theme from the app** — do not invent new palette colors.
- Tell the user the full path to open the file (browser or local static server).

## Rule 3 — Preview HTML structure

Every preview HTML file must include:

- `<!DOCTYPE html>`, `<html lang="en">`, charset + viewport meta.
- `<title>Preview — {Feature Name}</title>`
- Styles: prefer linking `../src/index.css` plus minimal page-local overrides only where needed for the mock layout.
- `<body>` with real styled markup for the feature being previewed.

## Rule 4 — Never use these as a “preview”

Do **not** present as a preview:

- ASCII box drawings (┌─┐│└─┘)
- Text-based tree structures
- Pseudocode layout descriptions
- Plain bullet lists pretending to be a UI mock
- Code snippets **as a substitute** for a rendered visual

If a real HTML preview cannot be produced, say:

**"I cannot generate a visual preview for this — would you like me to proceed directly to implementation?"**

## Rule 5 — Workflow for new features / redesigns

1. Describe the plan in plain language (no ASCII diagrams).
2. Ask: **"Would you like a visual preview before I build?"**
3. If **yes** → write the preview HTML under `previews/` and give the path; wait for feedback.
4. If **approved** → implement in the codebase.
5. If **changes** → update the preview HTML first, re-confirm, then implement.
6. Only then → commit (per user / branch policy).

## Rule 6 — Short reminder (also enforce Rules 1–5)

- Never show ASCII diagrams or text-tree previews as previews.
- Always ask the user before showing any preview.
- Previews must be real rendered HTML files in `previews/`.
- All UI elements must be proportional to their text size.
- Use existing app colors only — never invent new colors.
- Follow this order: plan → ask → preview → approve → build.
- Never auto-generate a preview without being asked.
